# WordPress Theme Development Rules for Cursor AI

## Project Context
This is a WordPress theme project named "GTS Theme" based on the Underscores (_s) starter theme. The theme uses:
- PHP for WordPress functionality
- SCSS for styling (compiled to CSS)
- JavaScript for interactive features
- WordPress Coding Standards for PHP
- WordPress Scripts for JavaScript/CSS linting

## Code Standards

### PHP
- Follow WordPress Coding Standards (WPCS)
- Use theme prefix `gts` for all functions, classes, and global variables
- Text domain: `gts-theme`
- Use tabs for indentation (not spaces)
- Always escape output with WordPress functions: `esc_html()`, `esc_attr()`, `esc_url()`, `wp_kses_post()`
- Always sanitize input with WordPress functions: `sanitize_text_field()`, `sanitize_email()`, etc.
- Use WordPress hooks (actions and filters) appropriately
- Follow WordPress naming conventions: functions use snake_case, classes use PascalCase

### JavaScript
- Follow WordPress JavaScript Coding Standards
- Use modern ES6+ syntax when appropriate
- Use WordPress dependencies (jQuery, lodash) when needed
- Enqueue scripts properly through `wp_enqueue_script()`

### CSS/SCSS
- Follow WordPress CSS Coding Standards
- Use BEM-like naming conventions
- Organize SCSS files in the sass/ directory structure
- Use variables and mixins from abstracts/
- Compile SCSS to CSS before committing

## WordPress Best Practices

### Security
- Always escape output
- Always sanitize input
- Use nonces for forms
- Use capability checks for admin functions
- Never use `eval()` or direct database queries without `$wpdb->prepare()`

### Performance
- Enqueue scripts and styles properly
- Use WordPress transients for caching when appropriate
- Minimize database queries
- Use WordPress object cache when available

### Template Hierarchy
- Follow WordPress template hierarchy
- Use template parts for reusable code
- Use `get_template_part()` for modular templates

### Hooks and Filters
- Use appropriate WordPress hooks
- Document custom hooks with `do_action()` and `apply_filters()`
- Use descriptive hook names with theme prefix: `gts_*`

## File Structure
- PHP template files in root: `header.php`, `footer.php`, `index.php`, etc.
- Template parts in `template-parts/`
- Functions in `functions.php` or `inc/` directory
- Styles in `sass/` directory (compiled to `style.css`)
- JavaScript in `js/` directory
- Assets (images, fonts) in `assets/` directory

## Development Guidelines
- Test in WordPress environment before committing
- Follow WordPress accessibility guidelines
- Ensure responsive design
- Test with different WordPress versions (minimum: 4.5)
- Check PHP compatibility (minimum: 5.6)

## When Writing Code
- Always provide context about what the code does
- Include PHPDoc comments for functions and classes
- Use meaningful variable and function names
- Keep functions focused and single-purpose
- Follow DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) principle
- Use WordPress functions instead of reinventing the wheel

## Common WordPress Functions to Use
- Template tags: `the_title()`, `the_content()`, `the_permalink()`, etc.
- Conditional tags: `is_front_page()`, `is_single()`, `is_page()`, etc.
- Query functions: `WP_Query`, `get_posts()`, `wp_get_recent_posts()`
- Utility functions: `get_template_directory_uri()`, `get_stylesheet_directory_uri()`
- Security functions: `wp_nonce_field()`, `wp_verify_nonce()`, `current_user_can()`
